"Lawrence A.J., Soame J.M.","The effects of climate change on the reproduction of coastal invertebrates",2004,"Ibis","146","SUPPL.1",,"29","39",,,10.1111/j.1474-919X.2004.00325.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33745029256&partnerID=40&md5=99477bf36850988811efd86c81b815d2","Department of Biological Sciences, University of Hull, Hull HU6 7RX, United Kingdom","Lawrence, A.J., Department of Biological Sciences, University of Hull, Hull HU6 7RX, United Kingdom; Soame, J.M., Department of Biological Sciences, University of Hull, Hull HU6 7RX, United Kingdom","Environmental cues control or synchronize the reproductive cycle of many marine invertebrates. Of these environmental cues, photoperiod and temperature have been shown to moderate reproduction either individually or in combination. In addition, they may act directly or, in the case of photoperiod, set circannual clock mechanisms. These environmental cues may affect a number of reproductive parameters, including sex determination, gametogenesis and spawning. Gonadotrophic and spawning hormones appear to act as the transducers between the environment and the gamete, and limited evidence indicates that temperature and photoperiod can alter levels of these. Such processes occur in a range of estuarine invertebrates that constitute important components of the diets of overwintering birds. Global warming is likely to uncouple and alter the phase relationship between temperature and photoperiod and this is likely to have significant consequences for animals that develop gametes during the winter and spawn in the spring in temperate northern latitudes. Species that cue reproduction to photoperiod are likely to be particularly vulnerable. Although this is unlikely to lead to extinctions, it may cause local extirpations. However, this will depend on speed of adaptation to changing climate in relation to speed of climate change and the degree of mixing between populations across the range of the species. More likely will be significant impacts on fecundity, spawning success and recruitment, and this may have significant implications for overwintering birds of national and international importance, and, ultimately, on the conservation status of estuaries such as the Humber in the UK. © 2004 British Ornithologists' Union.",,,,,,,,"Baduini, C.L., Hyrenbach, K.D., Coyle, K.O., Pinchuk, A., Mendenhall, V., Hunt, G.L., Mass mortality of Short-tailed Shearwaters in the South-Eastern Bering Sea during summer 1997 (2001) Fish Oceanogr., 10, pp. 117-130; Bartels-Hardege, H.D., Zeeck, E., Reproductive behaviour of Nereis diversicolor (Annelida: Polychaeta) (1990) Mar. Biol., 106, pp. 409-412; Bentley, M.G., Boyle, J., Pacey, A.A., (1994), pp. 37-44. , Environmental influences on endocrine systems controlling reproduction in polychaetes. In Dauvin, J.-C., Laubier, L. & Reish, D.J. (eds) Actes de la 4ème Conference Internationale Des Polychetes.Mem. Mus. Natn. Hist. Nat. 162: -Bentley, M.G., Pacey, A.A., Physiological and environmental control of reproduction in polychaetes (1992) Oceanogr. Mar. Biol. Ann. Rev., 30, pp. 433-481; Bhaud, M., Cha, J.H., Duchene, J.C., Nozias, C., On the influence of temperature on the marine fauna of the Western Mediterranean: a discussion (1995) J. Therm. Biol., 20, pp. 91-104; Boates, J.S., Goss-Custard, J.D., Foraging behaviour of Oystercatchers Haematopus ostralegus specialising on different species of prey (1992) Can. J. Zool., 70, pp. 2398-2404; Ceballos-Vazquez, B.P., Arellano-Martinez, M., Garcia-Dominguez, F., Villelejo-Fuerte, M., Gametogenesis of Pinna rugosa (Mollusca: Bivalvia) influenced by temperature and photoperiod (2000) J. Shellfish Res., 19, pp. 95-99; Chase, M.E., Thomas, M.L.H., The effect of the rate and onset of temperature increase on spawning in the periwinkle, Littorina littorea (L.) (1995) J. Exp. Mar. Biol. Ecol., 186, pp. 277-287; Chevalier, J., Godfrey, M., Gorodot, M., Significant difference of temperature dependent se